<br>
I believe both groups would benefit from reading this.  George R.R. Martin has completely blown me away with the &quot;Song of Fire and Ice&quot; series, starting with &quot;A Game of Thrones.&quot;<br>
<br>
It started decently enough, but the more you get into the story the more Martin throws the conventional thread of heroes defeating villians out the window.  Half of the time you don't even know who are the real villians.  Some of the characters that have been so reviled are easy to become sympathetic to as you learn more about them.  Martin creates real depth of characters here, not just throwaways.  And the people who seem so pivitol to the story are revealed to be not quite as important as they seemed, or simply killed as the story keeps going on in a slighty different direction.  There are deep plot twists that are completely unexpected, but not done simply for the sake of shock value.   I'm just about finished with with the third book and laughed outloud this morning at a twist that I absolutely did not see coming at all, and adds an amazing depth to the story as I really wonder what's coming next.  <br>
<br>
This series is really the best I've read in a long, long time.  I am sure some people wouldn't like it as it doesn't follow the tired formula of the reluctant hero overcoming all odds to defeat the evil villian.  <br>
<br>
My only complaint is that I'm going to have to wait for the fourth book.   <p>-Tain<BR>
