<br>
Characters are at point A on a map and need to get to point B. The world they cross is varied and interesting, but bascially the gist of the book is just them getting to point B so &quot;something&quot; can happen.<br>
<br>
In later books, (I think I read 4 or 5 before I gave up...the fact that I am not sure and haven't bothered to check speaks volumes), a few characters are at &quot;point C&quot; and a few others are at &quot;point D&quot; and they all have to get to &quot;point E.&quot; Again, this takes 600 pages.<br>
<br>
As the characters become more important in the world around them, they become less interesting. Martin's characters lose their importance, rise to power, grow up, live and die, and seem to develop...his internal monologues are all interesting. Sasha is very different from her sister Arya, Daenerys grows up and becomes a queen, but never loses her humanity. I dunno, I care about those characters...I can't remember the names of Jordan's. (Although I guess I can't spell Cersei.)<br>
<br>
There are these points in Martin's books, like the fight between the Viper and the Mountain, or the Red Wedding, where you just sit there stunned. Actually the second book is probably the most scene-setting--things happen but don't complete themselves until the third, but there's so much detail and groundwork in it that it is worth reading.<br>
<br>
Martin gives you glimpses of a world, legends, people's lives, details, stories, some are only half-completed...but that is really alot like life.<br>
